NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BPaul Bowyer: ^*N|cp||at|Play 
West has a quite horrible choice of opening leads (we bid Diamonds, don’t forget) so decides to plump for a trump. We have then to pause to Count and Plan. In terms of winners, there are obviously nine “on top” (one Spade, five Hearts, two Diamonds and a Club) so one extra needs to be found.|
PG| ***** 146 ***** |


NT|^b@2
Ruffing Spades in hand is futile (don’t ruff in the long trump hand) but a Diamond ruff is easy enough on table, in the short trump hand. So, we start by not drawing trumps and by playing the @DK, the @DA and a third Diamond. West plays a sly @DQ on this and we…?|
PG| ***** 147 ***** |


NT|^b@2
Now, this is a trap, cunningly set by West with his false-card in Diamonds. If we were to ruff this low, East would over-ruff with his @H6 and would return a trump, preventing any Diamond ruffs on table. Ouch! We can afford to ruff this Diamond with the @HK (we know trumps are not 5-0 after the opening trick) and now we have enough for the contract.|
PG| ***** 148 ***** |


NT|^b@2
True, had we been able to make a trick with the @H5, we could have also scored another Diamond ruff with the @HK and made an overtrick. Big deal. That would have been the right play in 5@H but not in 4@H. In most forms of bridge, the rewards for making overtricks are so small that they are not worth bothering with until the contract is as safe as the bank of - er, well as safe as something very safe.|
PG| ***** 149 ***** |


NT|^b@2

Here, we can subsequently draw trumps and take ten easy tricks, happily conceding the last three. 4@H making on the nose will do very nicely, thank-you.|
